 (mother tongue)—as merely the language of the home and the past—by returning to a time of great, if ironic, vibrancy, when Yiddish writers confronted the very nature of their existence in unprecedented ways. Under increasing pressure of news from the war front and silence from home, these writers re-imagined modernism, the Enlightenment, political engagement, literary conventions, and symbolic language.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Jewish.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150362671340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503626713423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503626713/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles